LIRNEasia is a pro-poor, pro-market think tank dedicated to catalysing policy change in the Asia Pacific region. LIRNEaisa conducts in-depth, policy-relevant research at the nexus of economics, technology, and law, using multidisciplinary approaches, and focusing on the following sectors: digital, labour, education, social safety nets, disability, energy, agriculture among others. Within the digital sector, LIRNEasia focuses on a multitude of digital regulation and policy issues, including access, digital rights, misinformation, and data protection. Its work on the information disorder has ranged from a scoping study of the information disorder across the Asia Pacific, to developing local language corpora and machine learning models and AI tools to explore the efficacy of algorithmic detection of misinformation, to understanding the impacts of the information disorder on elections and societies, testing solutions that might help counter it,  to systematically examining the effectiveness of various counter measures including digital literacy programmes.  

Acknowledging the substantial investment in digital technology, LIRNEasia recognises its potential for economic and social progress. However, LIRNEasia emphasises that digital solutions alone are not the answer to improving lives. With a strong focus on inclusion, LIRNEasia works towards dismantling barriers to digital access and use imposed by laws and regulations, aiming for inclusive progress through better knowledge, information, and technology access. Through in-depth research and documentation of regional good practices, the organisation disseminates actionable knowledge to policymakers, regulators, service providers, and the media. Recent examples include providing policy input into data protection, cyber security and online safety legislation.

Environmental Foundation (Guarantee) Limited is a public interest litigation organization in Sri Lanka with the tagline 'Justice for Nature', which has been in operation since 1981 with the objective of conserving Sri Lanka's natural resources through legal and scientific means. Our work ranges from litigation to conservation and scientific research, including collaborative efforts with government officials to develop national policies and legal reforms, implement projects and create awareness among the public.
primary_activities: Legal, Scientific Research, and Policy Analysis
main_delivery_mode: Research & Analysis, Ground level implementation - PET Collection, Legal Action

description: Rainforest Protectors of Sri Lanka is a non-profit environmental organization with a mission to protect the last remaining rainforests and threatened ecosystems in Sri Lanka including Sinharaja and Kanneliya rainforests through conservation projects and environmental activism primarily driven through volunteer support. Rainforest Protectors also engage in investigation, reporting and finding resolutions to urgent threats faced by our rainforests and wildlife through discussions with relevant authorities and stakeholders.

org_name: The Institute for Monitoring and Evaluation
description:
The Institute for Monitoring and Evaluation is a young institution, established in 2014 under the Companies Act of Sri Lanka with the exclusive purpose of bringing together experts from various disciplines to provide services for the State and Corporate sector institutions, Civil Society Organizations and the communities who are in need of ingenuous analysis, programs and evaluations on social, political, legal and economic disciplines to make a peaceful development in the country. 
TiME entered into the partnership with the Change the Game Academy in the Netherlands and have exclusive rights to conduct the training programs of the Change the Game Academy (CtGA -https://www.changethegameacademy.org/ 
   ) in Sri Lanka.  CtGA is the academic arm of the Wilde Ganzen Foundation in the Netherlands. Under this partnership, TiME is geared to build capacities of local CSOs and NGOs on the advocacy and lobby and Local Fund raising. Local Fundraising is a training module developed to find answers for the drying out of international funding to developing countries.  CtGA carries out these training programs in 15 countries in Africa, Asia, and Carribean region.
TiME is working towards becoming a leading training institution in advocacy and lobbying and local fundraising in Sri Lanka.
user_name: The Institute for Monitoring and Evaluation

org_name: RARE - Rally for Animal Rights & Enviornment
description:
We are an animal rights advocacy organisation with a vision to create a world where all sentient beings have equal rights and autonomy. Founded in 2019, we are a registered Non Profit Association in Sri Lanka. fdfdfdf

Sri Lanka is a biodiversity hotspot and home to asian elephant sub species Elephas maximus maximus and the species is listed "Endangered" by the IUCN. But Sri Lanka reports one of the worst human elephant conflict cases and one of the cruelest captive elephant industries of the world.

RARE has been recognised as the voice of the Sri Lankan elephant by elephant advocates and elephant lovers across the globe. 

Not just elephants we work to expose and fight against cruelty inflicted on all animals, whether they are wild, domesticated, farm or companion animals and We strive to make human beings understand that non humans have rights to mother earth just like humans and that right is not less than that of the humans.
user_name: RARE - Rally for Animal Rights & Enviornment

description:
Rainforest Protectors Trust focuses on saving real acres of rainforest in Sri Lanka through purchase and permanent conservation of privately held forest lands adjoining Sinharaja World Heritage Rainforest. Creating a Protected Buffer Zone for Sinharaja rainforest and a Biodiversity Forest Corridor to connect fragmented patches of forest to the North of Sinharaja is our top priority aimed at preventing encroachment of forest and deforestation.

Having lost more than 95% of the original rainforests during the past century, we are fighting against time to protect what is remaining in this vital ecosystem which is home to most of Sri Lanka's endemic and endangered flora and fauna.

description:
Established in 1994 in the Badulla district, HDFSL is a well-established community based
non-governmental organisation which now functions as national level Social Enterprise 
which has initiated and successfully completed projects in districts of Hambantota,Matara and Colombo working with and under the purview of both local and 
international organisations such as Asian Development Bank (ADB), UNDP, Ministry of 
Mahaweli Development & Environment, Environmental Authority and National Peace 
Council to name a few. HDFSL has an active member base of 600 who work on a voluntary 
basis and a permanent staff base of 15 who are being paid and sustained for over a period 
of 29 years. The staffs at HDFSL are experienced, exposed and well-connected which has 
helped the organisation to deliver the projects they undertake quit successfully and 
efficiently.
